<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-precalc-absval" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Absolute Values</title>

  <p>
    Absolute value equations appear frequently in algebra and calculus.
    They are used to describe distance, error bounds, and tolerances.
    The emphasis is on understanding what absolute value means
    and applying that meaning systematically.
  </p>






  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-abs-definitions">
    <title>Definitions of Absolute Value</title>


  <definition xml:id="def-absolute-value">
  <title>Absolute Value</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      For any real number <m>A</m>, the <term>absolute value</term> of <m>A</m>, written <m>|A|</m>, is defined by
    </p>
    <me>
      |A| = \begin{cases}
        A, \amp \text{if } A \geq 0, \\\\
        -A, \amp \text{if } A \le 0.
      \end{cases}
    </me>
    <p>
      Geometrically, <m>|A|</m> represents the distance from <m>A</m> to <m>0</m> on the number line.
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>  



    
    <remark>
      <p>
        These two definitions describe the same quantity.
        The distance definition is often more intuitive,
        while the piecewise definition is more useful for algebraic manipulation.
      </p>
    </remark>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-abs-basic-equations">
    <title>Solving Basic Absolute Value Equations</title>

    <p>
      We begin with equations of the form <m>|A| = c</m>,
      where <m>c</m> is a nonnegative number.
    </p>

    <principle xml:id="pr-abs-equals-constant">
      <statement>
        <p>
          If <m>c &gt; 0</m>, then
        </p>
        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
|A| = c &amp; \Longleftrightarrow &amp; A = c \quad \text{or} \quad A = -c.
\end{array}
        </me>
      </statement>
    </principle>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve <m>|x| = 5</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The distance from <m>x</m> to <m>0</m> is <m>5</m>.
          This occurs at two points.
        </p>
        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
x = 5 \quad \text{or} \quad x = -5
\end{array}
        </me>
      </solution>
    </example>

 
    
<example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve <m>|2x - 3| = 7</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Step 1: Write two equations.
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
2x - 3 &amp; = &amp; 7 \\
2x - 3 &amp; = &amp; -7
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          Step 2: Solve each equation.
        </p>

        <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
2x = 10 &amp; \Rightarrow &amp; x = 5 \\[0.4em]
2x = -4 &amp; \Rightarrow &amp; x = -2
\end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          The solution set is <m>x= -2</m> or <m>x= 5</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Solve <m>|x^2 - 1| = 8</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      Step 1: Use the definition of absolute value to write two equations.
    </p>

    <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
x^2 - 1 &amp; = &amp; 8 \\
x^2 - 1 &amp; = &amp; -8
\end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      Step 2: Solve each equation separately.
    </p>

    <p>
      First equation:
    </p>

    <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
x^2 - 1 &amp; = &amp; 8 \\
x^2 &amp; = &amp; 9 \\
x &amp; = &amp; \pm 3
\end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      Second equation:
    </p>

    <me>
\begin{array}{rcl}
x^2 - 1 &amp; = &amp; -8 \\
x^2 &amp; = &amp; -7
\end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      This equation has no real solutions.
    </p>

    <p>
      Step 3: Combine the solutions.
    </p>

    <p>
      The solution set is <m>x = -3</m> or <m>x = 3</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>

  </subsection>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->


  <!-- ======================================================= -->
  <subsection xml:id="ssec-abs-no-solution">
    <title>When Absolute Value Equations Have No Solution</title>

    <p>
      Absolute value is never negative.
      This observation allows us to immediately identify equations
      that have no solution.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve <m>|x - 4| = -3</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Since absolute value is always nonnegative,
          this equation has no solution.
        </p>

      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <!-- ======================================================= -->
 


</section>